SIMPLE: mangrove
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Mangrove
<hw>Man"grove</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Malay
<ets>manggi-manggi</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>The
name of one or two trees of the genus <gen>Rhizophora</gen>
(<spn>Rhizophora Mangle</spn>, and <spn>Rhizophora mucronata</spn>, the
last doubtfully distinct) inhabiting muddy shores of tropical regions,
where they spread by emitting aerial roots, which fasten in the saline
mire and eventually become new stems. The seeds also send down a strong
root while yet attached to the parent plant.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The fruit has a ruddy brown shell, and a delicate white
pulp which is sweet and eatable. The bark is astringent, and is used for
tanning leather. The black and the white mangrove (<spn>Avicennia
nitida</spn> and <spn>Avicennia tomentosa</spn>) have much the same
habit.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The mango fish.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mangrove family</ent>⟦br⟧
